Neural Networks and Machine Learning

VGG¶

VGG is a convolutional neural network which is primarily focused on large-scale image recognition. This architecture was used to win ILSVR (ImageNet) competition in 2014, achieving 92.7% top-5 test accuracy in ImageNet. It is one of the most widely used CNN and very simple to implement, so it is highly documented and analyzed online. It is sometimes considered a building block for educational purposes due to its ease of use. This is one of the reasons that this CNN was chosen.

Among the analyses online that is available about it is the OpenAI Microscope feature visualization. This allows us to look through the layers and channels of the network and made it easy to select a filter to use in this lab. Another important reason could be that any doubt about the structure or characteristics of the network could be easily answered through an online search. Finally, this is a simple network to analyze since it has a simple architecture and doesn't include complex feed forward operations that could make the analysis of the excitations and inhibitions of filters difficult. On the results of the Lamp Image, the filter is excited by the edges of the books and the base of the lamp and by the head of the horse figure.

Gradient descent to find the image that maximize activation¶

The following code was made by analyzing the work of F. Chollet. [2] To understand the output of the filter, an image that will maximally excite it will be created through code and gradient descent.

A new model for VGG19 will be created from the keras package, but it will not include the top dense layers. This is because this are not needed, they are used for classification and we will only analyze the output of the chosen filter.

In [12]:
# Disabling eager execution in order to use gradient functions.
tf.compat.v1.disable_eager_execution()
In [112]:
# New model without top dense layers, include_top=False
model = VGG19(weights='imagenet', include_top=False)

# Select layer and filter, same as the previous example.
layerName = 'block4_conv3'
filterIndex = 196

layerOutput = model.get_layer(layerName).output

To make the gradient descent, a function to optimize needs to be established. This will be the loss function. This function will take into account the output of our chosen filter and get its mean value. For the filter to show high excitation, this number will need to be very high, meaning that the whole image is exciting the filter.

By taking the gradient of this function, we will make sure that this function can be optimized. The value of the gradient with respect to the model input can indicate how much needs to be added or substracted to the original input to achieve maximal excitation, since the gradient is taken with respect to the input.

With this information, a new function can be made with the Keras Function. It will take as input a Tensor and output the two desired tensors: the loss function and the gradient. This function will be calld iterate, since the gradient can indicate the direction that will achieve an image that can maximally excite the filter, but in step intervals as we optimize it.

In [115]:
# We define loss function to which we will apply gradient descent
lossFunction = tf.keras.backend.mean(layerOutput[:, :, :, filterIndex])

#We take the gradient of the loss function with respect to the input
grads = tf.keras.backend.gradients(lossFunction, model.input)[0]b

#We make a function that given the input tensor will use to make the two desired outputs, 
#The loss gradient to minimize and the gradient that will help change the image Tensor
iterate = tf.keras.backend.function([model.input], [lossFunction, grads])
In [147]:
# Defining the function that maximize the filter activation, using the above

def maximize_filter(layer_name, filter_index):
    
    layerOutput = model.get_layer(layer_name).output
    
    # create a loss function and apply gradient descent
    lossFunction = tf.keras.backend.mean(layerOutput[:, :, :, filter_index])
    
    grads = tf.keras.backend.gradients(lossFunction, model.input)[0]
    
    # Normalization of the gradient using method seen in F.Chollet
    grads /= (tf.keras.backend.sqrt(tf.keras.backend.mean(tf.keras.backend.square(grads))) + 1e-5)
    
    iterate = tf.keras.backend.function([model.input], [lossFunction, grads])
    
    # We make a noise image with the desired size for VGG19
    input_img_data = np.random.random((1, 224, 224, 3)) 
    
    # We loop the gradient descent strategy with a delta step
    step = 1
    for i in range(60):
        # Compute the loss value and gradient valueab
        loss_value, grads_value = iterate([input_img_data])
        # Here we adjust the input image in the direction that maximizes the loss
        input_img_data += grads_value * step
        
    return input_img_data

# We need to process the image once this is done because the plotting of the obtained values need to be between [0 , 255]
def processing_image(image):
    
    #Center values around zero mean, this will enhace the contrast in the final image
    image -= image.mean()
    image /= (image.std() + 1e-5)
    image *= 0.1
    
    # Clip values to bound the values between [0,1]
    image += 0.5
    image = np.clip(image, 0, 1)
    
    # make values in range [0,255] to create an RGB array
    image *= 255
    image = np.clip(image, 0, 255).astype('uint8')
    
    return image

To use the function that we created, the selected layer and filter will be given to the function. With this, the image that will maximally excite the filter can be created.

In [120]:
# Specify the parameters for the filter
layer_name = 'block4_conv3'
filter_index = [196]

# Use the gradient descent function and process the resulting image
image = maximize_filter(layer_name, filter_index[0])[0]
image = processing_image(image)

# Show the results
plt.title("Filter" + str(filter_index[0]))
plt.imshow(image, cmap="hsv")
plt.show()

Result Hypothesis: At first glance, it would appear that an image with curves excites the filter. This filter extracts curves oriented to the lower left side of the image. Inside of the network it could be part of a circuit with other curve filters to detect round edges and curves that are orientation variant in images.

This can also be verified by the AI Microscope tool, were the filter is mostly excited by images related to curve edges (e.g. quarters of clocks, bike wheels, rackets, etc. all oriented to the bottom left corner). [3]

Image of the feature visualization unit 196 taken from the Microscope AI.

Visualizing convolutional filters from the circuit¶

The next step would be to analyze the filters that form the input for the chosen filter. To do so, the convolutional layer 'block4_conv2' will be anlyzed. This layer contains information about the incoming activations for filter 196.

In [48]:
# Taking the layer and its weights to analyze incoming activations
filters, biases = model.get_layer('block4_conv2').get_weights()
print("block4_conv2", filters.shape)

block4_conv2 (3, 3, 512, 512)

Taking the L2 norm over all the incoming activations for the unit 196. After getting all the norms, we sorted the results to obtain the filters with the strongest weights. The top 6 strongest will be chosen.

In [137]:
# Array to store the L2 norms of the weights
weights_norm = []
for i in range(512):
    
    # The norm is taken from each filter that influences on the unit 196
    weights_norm.append(np.linalg.norm(filters[:,:,i,196]))
    
# List is sorted according to the highest norms
top_six = np.argsort(weights_norm)[-6:]

The next figures show the results of the filters by plotting the filter coefficients of the first six. We consider that these will have the most influence on the filter unit 196 because after walking through the 512 filters that influence on the layer and this unit, these 6 filters had the strongest activation because they held the highest absolute values on their coefficients through the norm. This is because the magnitude of the matrix, norm, that makes up the filter is related directly to the strength of the influence of activation of the filter. In this part we do not consider if the filter will be excitatory or inhibitory.

In [135]:
# Plotting of the filters
for i in range(6):
    ax = plt.subplot(3, 2, i+1)
    plt.imshow(filters[:,:,top_six[i],196], cmap='seismic')
    plt.title('Filter '+str(top_six[i]))
    plt.colorbar()
    plt.axis('off')

The filter plots can be interpreted by the color: the blue part indicates inhibitions or negative coefficients, while red color indicates the excitations or positive coefficients. These will influece on the filter 196 on the next convolutional layer, the filter that was originaly chosen because their norm are the strongest. To consider the type of influence they will have on the the filter we consider two factors: the amounnt of positive coefficients versus negative coefficients a filter has, and the mean value of the coefficients. In this part we do consider the positive or negative value of the coefficients, hence considering if they are excitatory or inhibitory.

The filters that have a positive mean value and more positive coefficients than negative ones (at least 5 positive coefficients) will be excitatory. Otherwise they will be inhibitory.

In [138]:
for i in top_six:
    # getting a deep copy from one of the top six filters.
    mat = filters[:, :, i, 196].copy()
    
    # calculating how many positive coefficients are in each filter
    positive_coeffs = len(mat[np.where( mat > 0)])
    
    # getting the mean value of the filter
    mean_value = mat.mean()
    
    # printing results
    print("Filter", i ,"had", positive_coeffs, "possitive coefficients.", "Mean Value:",  mean_value)
    

Filter 434 had 6 possitive coefficients. Mean Value: 0.006557192
Filter 178 had 6 possitive coefficients. Mean Value: 0.0073837745
Filter 302 had 7 possitive coefficients. Mean Value: 0.0059446497
Filter 448 had 5 possitive coefficients. Mean Value: 0.005343188
Filter 395 had 6 possitive coefficients. Mean Value: 0.00656599
Filter 206 had 7 possitive coefficients. Mean Value: 0.019114725

With the results, we can conclude that all the filters are excitatory for the filter 196.

Maximizing activation on filters¶

As we did before, the gradient ascent in input space through gradient descent of the excitatory filters will be applied to create an image that will maximally excite each of the filters. This will allow us to consider how these filters form a cirtcuit that can contribute to the detection of certain features.

We use the function that was used in the previous section.

In [148]:
# Defining the layer of the excitatory filters
layer_name2 = 'block4_conv2'

# The index of the excitatory filters taken from previous section
filter_index2 = top_six

# Using the previous functions
for i in range(6):
    image2 = maximize_filter(layer_name2, filter_index2[i])[0]
    image2 = processing_image(image2)
    
    # subplotting each filter
    plt.title("Filter " + str(filter_index2[i]))
    plt.imshow(image2, cmap="hsv")
    plt.show()

We can try to interpret these results. Taking into account the assumptions made at the beginning of the lab, these filters seem to make a circuit that is excited by features related to curves and textures.

We can visualize the circuit formed for unit 196 through the weights that connect it to the 6 filters that are most influential on it.

The hypothesis was that filter 196 was activated by curves directed toward the lower left corner of an image. The downstream clients of curves are ones that involve curves. [4] In this case, all the top six filters involve them.

Filter 434 is maximally excited by a pattern of small circles, which could be used to detect eyes or coins. Filter 178 is maximally excited by curved lines that stream diagonally. They could most likely detect edges or diagonal compositions, such as lines or structures. Filter 302 is maximally excited by curves facing the lower left corner, but they seem to be more flat than those appeared for filter 196. Filter 448 is maximally excited by rhombuses with round edges. They can resemble holes or images that have dots with high contrast. Filter 395 is maximally excited by lines facing diagonally. They seem rounded, almost like cables. They could detect edges and slight curves on images. Filter 206 is maximally excited by high contrast texture, similar to circular bumps. They could be used to detect contrast patterns in depth or color in an image.

Conclusion¶

Overall the circuit can detect curves and edges. It contains filters that detect from curves lines to quarters of circles. This seems to indicate that the circuit will be able to detect curves that are variant in curvature and space.

The filter we originally chose, 196, most likely is part of a larger circuit which can detect position invariant curves and edges, as well as high contrast texture, as shown by the input activations.
